title: For Sale:  Early Chinese Type 56 SKS with Blade Style Bayonett
postcontent:
This is from the latest batch of C&R eligible early arsenal /26\ SKS with the blade style bayonet.  

I did the hard work of cleaning all of the cosmoline off the rifle.  These are conflict rifles used in Albania (more on that below.)  I cleaned all the grime off the stock, but was sure to keep the "been there, done that" look of the stock with all the dings and gashes. I applied about 10 coats of boiled linseed oil to seal and protect the stock.

The bore is chrome lined and excellent.  Almost looks brand new.  The bluing is intact and there's sights of light pitting in only a few of the areas.  The gas tube was a little rough, but I worked it a bit to smoothen it out and now the tube moves inside like glas. 

The history behind these latest batches of SKS's because they're the only Chinese SKS's that are C&R eligible and because where they were used. These came from the Balkans, most likely from Albania.  Some of the SKS's had initials and other trench art that points to Albania, with some of the rifles even having Albanian style SKS stocks and bolts.  This is also the reason why these batch of Chinese SKS's are C&R eligible.  You can read more about these latest imports at www.sksboards.com and click on the Chinese section of the forums.

I originally bought this with the intention of doing a bubba job and converting it into a bullpup.  However, I decided to keep it, as is.  With that said, money is short and out of my collection this is the one I'd probably shoot the least and has the least sentimental value, so it's up for sale now.
